Perhaps you'd disagree if you were the one under the control of an evil tyrant.  Seems very self serving to me that you are against any type of military intervention while your own life is very comfortable and you are personally free to live your life in peace.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I believe that an attack on the US was inevitable. And I am surprised that it took as long as it did.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree with this, and I'm sure there will be more attacks.  However, I don't think that should have anything to do with the course of action we take.  In other words, I would not have a small number of tyrants hold us hostage with the fear that doing the right thing will lead to retaliatory action.  Our decisions should be based on what is the right thing to do without regard for retaliation from the evildoers of the world.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The world would be great if we could solve our differences diplomatically.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes it would, but we don't live in that world.  There are those that will only yield to force.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Prove to me that you've been doing the right thing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Prove to me that we haven't.  The bottom line is that we must do what our consciences dictate is the morally correct thing for us to do.<br>
